```cpp
static BCLog::Logger logger;
return logger;
```

> ```c++
> static BCLog::Logger logger;
> return logger;
> ```

The `logger` object could (potentially) be destroyed before its last use at program exit sequence that leads to undefined behavior.

Is  this something inherent to `thread_local` to construct on first use?

Running this example program:

```cpp
struct Foo {
    Mutex m_mut;
    Foo()
    {
        std::cout << __LINE__ << __func__ << std::endl;
        LOCK(m_mut);
    }
    ~Foo()
    {
        std::cout << __LINE__ << __func__ << std::endl;
        LOCK(m_mut);
    }
};

void initialize()

@MarcoFalke 

I can confirm that the following patch fixes all of the memory errors mentioned in this pull:
```diff
diff --git a/src/sync.cpp b/src/sync.cpp
index 41c75302d..9b99f5cfa 100644
--- a/src/sync.cpp
+++ b/src/sync.cpp
@@ -89,7 +89,12 @@ LockData& GetLockData() {
     return *lockdata;
 }
 
-static thread_local LockStack g_lockstack;
+LockStack& GetLockStack() {

```suggestion
    // The operating system automatically reclaims all the memory in a program's heap when that program exits.
    // Since the destructor is never called, the object and all its members must have an implicit destructor.
```
